<subSubSection id="C322B4E76672FFC2FF0B055D6AC39B72" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B87E76C6672FFC2FF0B055D6A609AE6" blockId="20.[151,1437,589,1228]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FF0B055D696F9A79" bold="true" box="[151,305,589,616]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species occurs throughout the northern GOM in shallow waters, including bays and estuaries. Although it can be found from the Texas/ 
<collectingCountry id="F32FA7FC6672FFC2FDFC05616AEB9A9A" box="[608,693,625,651]" name="Mexico" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Mexico</collectingCountry>
border to southern Florida, there is some evidence that this species may be more prevalent in the northeastern than in the northwestern GOM (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FC4A05856CC99ABE" author="Jones, C. M. &amp; Hoffmayer, E. R. &amp; Hendon, J. M. &amp; Quattro, J. M. &amp; Lewandowski, J. &amp; Roberts, M. A. &amp; Poulakis, G. R. &amp; Ajemian, M. J. &amp; Driggers, W. B. &amp; de Carvalho, M. R. &amp; Rego, M. G. &amp; Hazin, F. H. V. &amp; Marquez-Farias, J. F." box="[982,1175,661,687]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="499 - 514" refId="ref18195" refString="Jones, C. M., Hoffmayer, E. R., Hendon, J. M., Quattro, J. M., Lewandowski, J., Roberts, M. A., Poulakis, G. R., Ajemian, M. J., Driggers, W. B., de Carvalho, M. R., Rego, M. G., Hazin, F. H. V. &amp; Marquez-Farias, J. F. (2017) Morphological conservation of rays in the genus Rhinoptera (Elasmobranchii, Rhinopteridae) conceals the occurrence of a large batoid, Rhinoptera brasiliensis Muller, in the northern Gulf of Mexico. Zootaxa, 4286 (4), 499 - 514. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4286.4.3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Jones 
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FB8005866C0A9ABE" box="[1052,1108,661,687]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
). This species regularly occurs from close to shore out to waters 
<quantity id="4CC04A896672FFC2FDFE05A96AC29AC5" box="[610,668,697,724]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" unit="m" value="30.0">30 m</quantity>
in depth, although NMFS SEFSC trawl surveys have captured individuals in waters up to 
<quantity id="4CC04A896672FFC2FE0005CD698B9AE9" box="[412,469,733,760]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.6" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" unit="m" value="96.0">96 m</quantity>
in depth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87E76C6672FFC2FF5B04116AC39B72" blockId="20.[151,1437,589,1228]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FF5B041169919B0D" bold="true" box="[199,463,769,796]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">First Record in GOM.</emphasis>
The first record of this species occurring in the northern 
<materialsCitation id="3B50ED316672FFC2FBD904116AC79B72" collectingDate="1887" collectingDateMax="1889" collectingDateMin="1887" collectionCode="GOM" collectorName="Silas Stearns" location="Pensacola" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" specimenCode="USNM 21221" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Florida">
<collectionCode id="ED297FA96672FFC2FBD904116CD89B0A" box="[1093,1158,769,795]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">GOM</collectionCode>
is a report by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FABF0411697C9B2E" author="Goode, G. B. &amp; Bean, T. H." pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="121 - 156" refId="ref17474" refString="Goode, G. B. &amp; Bean, T. H. (1879) Catalogue of a collection of fishes sent from Pensacola, Florida, and vicinity, by Mr. Silas Stearns, with descriptions of six new species. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 2 (74), 121 - 156. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.2 - 74.121" type="journal article" year="1879">Goode and Bean (1879)</bibRefCitation>
of a single specimen (
<specimenCode id="DB9E4F176672FFC2FD8204356A9F9B2E" box="[542,705,805,831]" collectionCode="USNM" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" type="Museum">USNM 21221</specimenCode>
, verified by first author) collected by 
<collectorName id="26CD82BA6672FFC2FBF504356CA69B2E" box="[1129,1272,805,831]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Silas Stearns</collectorName>
between 
<date id="FF86C1AC6672FFC2FAF8043568A19B72" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" value="1887" valueMax="1889">
<collectingDate id="EFC238446672FFC2FAF8043568A19B72" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" value="1887" valueMax="1889">
1887 and 
<quantity id="4CC04A896672FFC2FF5B045968A19B72" box="[199,255,841,867]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.79806" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" unit="in" value="1889.0">1889</quantity>
</collectingDate>
</date>
in the vicinity of 
<location id="8EE7B1B76672FFC2FE5B04596A649B72" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0391567A6672FFC2FF0B06396B269CDD:8EE7B1B76672FFC2FE5B04596A649B72" box="[455,570,841,867]" name="Pensacola" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" stateProvince="Florida">Pensacola</location>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49FC298E6672FFC2FDD804596AC79B72" box="[580,665,841,867]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Florida</collectingRegion>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C322B4E76672FFC2FF5B047E6B269CDD" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B87E76C6672FFC2FF5B047E6C749C92" blockId="20.[151,1437,589,1228]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FF5B047E69659B99" bold="true" box="[199,315,878,904]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Remarks.</emphasis>
Recent studies (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FE63047D6A829B96" author="Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Caira, J. N. &amp; Jensen, K. &amp; Rosana, K. A. M. &amp; White, W. T. &amp; Last, P. R." box="[511,732,877,904]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="1 - 262" refId="ref19315" refString="Naylor, G. J. P., Caira, J. N., Jensen, K., Rosana, K. A. M., White, W. T. &amp; Last, P. R. (2012) A DNA sequence based approach to the identification of shark and ray species and its implications for global elasmobranch diversity and parasitology. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 367, 1 - 262, 102 figs., 5 tbs. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 754.1" type="book chapter" year="2012">
Naylor 
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FDC6047E6AD19B96" box="[602,655,877,903]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FD77047E6BE89B96" author="Jones, C. M. &amp; Hoffmayer, E. R. &amp; Hendon, J. M. &amp; Quattro, J. M. &amp; Lewandowski, J. &amp; Roberts, M. A. &amp; Poulakis, G. R. &amp; Ajemian, M. J. &amp; Driggers, W. B. &amp; de Carvalho, M. R. &amp; Rego, M. G. &amp; Hazin, F. H. V. &amp; Marquez-Farias, J. F." box="[747,950,877,904]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="499 - 514" refId="ref18195" refString="Jones, C. M., Hoffmayer, E. R., Hendon, J. M., Quattro, J. M., Lewandowski, J., Roberts, M. A., Poulakis, G. R., Ajemian, M. J., Driggers, W. B., de Carvalho, M. R., Rego, M. G., Hazin, F. H. V. &amp; Marquez-Farias, J. F. (2017) Morphological conservation of rays in the genus Rhinoptera (Elasmobranchii, Rhinopteridae) conceals the occurrence of a large batoid, Rhinoptera brasiliensis Muller, in the northern Gulf of Mexico. Zootaxa, 4286 (4), 499 - 514. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4286.4.3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Jones 
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FCA9047E6B2F9B96" box="[821,881,877,903]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
) have indicated the presence of a second rhinopterid species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C389CEF6672FFC2FEE004816B7C9BBA" authority="Muller, 1836" authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1836" box="[380,802,913,939]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Rhinoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FEE004816ADA9BBA" box="[380,644,913,939]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Rhinoptera brasiliensis</emphasis>
Müller, 1836
</taxonomicName>
, in the northern GOM (see below). The two species are morphologically very similar and therefore difficult to differentiate without detailed examination and/or genetic verification. It is likely, based upon historic reports (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FD7204C96C639BE5" author="Bigelow, H. B. &amp; Schroeder, W. C." box="[750,1085,985,1012]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="1 - 514" refId="ref15696" refString="Bigelow, H. B. &amp; Schroeder, W. C. (1953) Sawfishes, guitarfishes, skates and rays. Chimaeroids. In: Tee-Van, J., Breder, C. M., Hildebrand, S. F., Parr, A. E. &amp; Schroeder, W. C. (Eds.), Fishes of the Western North Atlantic. Part 2. Sears Foundation for Marine Research, Yale Univ., New Haven, pp. 1 - 514. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / j. ctvbcd 0 f 3.5" type="book chapter" year="1953">Bigelow and Schroeder 1953</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FBD404CA6D029BE2" author="Acero, A. P. &amp; Garzon, J. F." box="[1096,1372,985,1012]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="9 - 11" refId="ref15293" refString="Acero, A. P. &amp; Garzon, J. F. (1982) On an interesting specimen of cow nose ray (Pisces: Rhinopteridae) from the colombian Caribbean. Boletim do Instituto Oceanografico da Universidade de Sao Paulo, 31 (2), 9 - 11. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0373 - 55241982000200003" type="journal article" year="1982">Acero and Garzon 1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FAF504C969D19C09" author="Isais, M. G. &amp; Dominguez, H. M. M." pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="947 - 948" refId="ref18112" refString="Isais, M. G. &amp; Dominguez, H. M. M. (1996) First record of Rhinoptera brasiliensis (Batoidei: Rhinopteridae) in Veracruz, Mexico. Revista de Biologia Tropical, 44 (2 B), 947 - 948." type="journal article" year="1996">Isaís and Dominguez 1996</bibRefCitation>
), that 
<taxonomicName id="4C389CEF6672FFC2FE4A04ED6A839C06" authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1836" box="[470,733,1021,1047]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Rhinoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FE4A04ED6A839C06" box="[470,733,1021,1047]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Rhinoptera brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been present in the northern GOM for several decades, if not longer, bringing into question the validity of reports and research focusing on this species without confirming species identity (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA99A9D6672FFC2FECF03556A489C4E" author="Jones, C. M. &amp; Hoffmayer, E. R. &amp; Hendon, J. M. &amp; Quattro, J. M. &amp; Lewandowski, J. &amp; Roberts, M. A. &amp; Poulakis, G. R. &amp; Ajemian, M. J. &amp; Driggers, W. B. &amp; de Carvalho, M. R. &amp; Rego, M. G. &amp; Hazin, F. H. V. &amp; Marquez-Farias, J. F." box="[339,534,1093,1119]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301" pagination="499 - 514" refId="ref18195" refString="Jones, C. M., Hoffmayer, E. R., Hendon, J. M., Quattro, J. M., Lewandowski, J., Roberts, M. A., Poulakis, G. R., Ajemian, M. J., Driggers, W. B., de Carvalho, M. R., Rego, M. G., Hazin, F. H. V. &amp; Marquez-Farias, J. F. (2017) Morphological conservation of rays in the genus Rhinoptera (Elasmobranchii, Rhinopteridae) conceals the occurrence of a large batoid, Rhinoptera brasiliensis Muller, in the northern Gulf of Mexico. Zootaxa, 4286 (4), 499 - 514. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4286.4.3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Jones 
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FE060356698C9C4E" box="[410,466,1093,1119]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
). Care should be taken in applying the results of research focused on this species in the northern GOM until species-specific results can be obtained and compared.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87E76C6672FFC2FF5B039D6B269CDD" blockId="20.[151,1437,589,1228]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">
<emphasis id="B94C3B7E6672FFC2FF5B039D699F9CB9" bold="true" box="[199,449,1165,1192]" pageId="20" pageNumber="301">Conservation Status.</emphasis>
Near Threatened, although this status will likely change given the recent identification of a congener co-occurring throughout most of the species’ range.
</paragraph>
